WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.860 --> 00:00:14.515
So a few years ago,
几年前，

2
00:00:14.539 --> 00:00:17.476
I did something really brave,
我做了一些非常勇敢的事，

3
00:00:17.500 --> 00:00:20.180
or some would say really stupid.
或许有些人会说很愚蠢的事。

4
00:00:20.660 --> 00:00:21.980
I ran for Congress.
我参选国会议员。

5
00:00:22.860 --> 00:00:26.596
For years, I had existed safely behind the scenes in politics
很多年来，我安全地存在于 政治活动背后

6
00:00:26.620 --> 00:00:29.676
as a fundraiser, as an organizer,
作为资金筹集人，作为组织者，

7
00:00:29.700 --> 00:00:32.900
but in my heart, I always wanted to run.
但我的内心， 我一直希望参选。

8
00:00:33.500 --> 00:00:37.956
The sitting congresswoman had been in my district since 1992.
我所在选区的国会议员女士 从1992年起担任这个职务。

9
00:00:37.980 --> 00:00:39.876
She had never lost a race,
她从未输过一场选战，

10
00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:43.780
and no one had really even run against her in a Democratic primary.
没有人真正认真地 在民主选举中与她竞争。

11
00:00:44.500 --> 00:00:47.356
But in my mind, this was my way
但在我心中，这就是我

12
00:00:47.380 --> 00:00:48.876
to make a difference,
创造不同的方式，

13
00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:51.020
to disrupt the status quo.
改变现状。

14
00:00:51.780 --> 00:00:55.140
The polls, however, told a very different story.
民意调查，然而， 显示出完全不同的故事。

15
00:00:55.740 --> 00:00:58.956
My pollsters told me that I was crazy to run,
我的民调专家告诉我 我要参选简直疯了，

16
00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:01.900
that there was no way that I could win.
我不可能会赢。

17
00:01:02.580 --> 00:01:03.916
But I ran anyway,
但我还是参选了，

18
00:01:03.940 --> 00:01:09.116
and in 2012, I became an upstart in a New York City congressional race.
在2012年，我成了崛起的新秀 参选纽约市国会竞选。

19
00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:12.220
I swore I was going to win.
我发誓我会赢。

20
00:01:12.820 --> 00:01:15.436
I had the endorsement from the New York Daily News,
我得到了《纽约每日新闻》的认可，

21
00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:18.796
the Wall Street Journal snapped pictures of me on election day,
《华尔街日报》刊登了我在选举日的照片，

22
00:01:18.820 --> 00:01:22.420
and CNBC called it one of the hottest races in the country.
美国全国广播公司财经频道称之为 全国范围内最热的选战。

23
00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:25.516
I raised money from everyone I knew,
我从我认识的每个人那里筹钱，

24
00:01:25.540 --> 00:01:27.436
including Indian aunties
包括印度阿姨们

25
00:01:27.460 --> 00:01:30.180
that were just so happy an Indian girl was running.
她们很高兴一个印度女生参选。

26
00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:34.236
But on election day, the polls were right,
但选举日，民调是对的，

27
00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:37.300
and I only got 19 percent of the vote,
我只拿到了19%的选票，

28
00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:41.476
and the same papers that said I was a rising political star
那张曾称我为新兴政治明星的报纸

29
00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:45.916
now said I wasted 1.3 million dollars
现在却说我浪费了130万美金

30
00:01:45.940 --> 00:01:50.956
on 6,321 votes.
在6321张选票上。

31
00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:52.260
Don't do the math.
不要算数字。

32
00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:55.300
It was humiliating.
太丢脸了。

33
00:01:56.140 --> 00:01:58.796
Now, before you get the wrong idea,
现在，在你们得到错误观点前，

34
00:01:58.820 --> 00:02:01.260
this is not a talk about the importance of failure.
这不是一个讲述 失败有多重要的演说。

35
00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:03.500
Nor is it about leaning in.
也不是说女孩要向前一步。

36
00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:07.436
I tell you the story of how I ran for Congress
我讲述的故事是 我如何参选国会议员的

37
00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:09.916
because I was 33 years old
因为我只有33岁

38
00:02:09.940 --> 00:02:14.676
and it was the first time in my entire life
这是我人生中第一次

39
00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:18.356
that I had done something that was truly brave,
做出真正勇敢的事，

40
00:02:18.380 --> 00:02:21.060
where I didn't worry about being perfect.
没有担心完美。

41
00:02:21.459 --> 00:02:22.916
And I'm not alone:
我不是一个人：

42
00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:24.676
so many women I talk to tell me
太多女士曾告诉我

43
00:02:24.700 --> 00:02:27.596
that they gravitate towards careers and professions
她们多么被职业和专业吸引

44
00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:29.716
that they know they're going to be great in,
她们知道她们会做得很好，

45
00:02:29.740 --> 00:02:32.116
that they know they're going to be perfect in,
她们知道她们会非常完美，

46
00:02:32.140 --> 00:02:33.956
and it's no wonder why.
不足为奇。

47
00:02:33.980 --> 00:02:37.036
Most girls are taught to avoid risk and failure.
绝大多数的女孩被教育 来规避风险和失败。

48
00:02:37.060 --> 00:02:38.836
We're taught to smile pretty,
我们被教育要有漂亮的微笑，

49
00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:41.380
play it safe, get all A's.
不要冒险，课程拿全A。

50
00:02:42.140 --> 00:02:43.836
Boys, on the other hand,
男孩们，另一方面来说，

51
00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:46.636
are taught to play rough, swing high,
被教育成要更加勇猛， 冲击更高的目标，

52
00:02:46.660 --> 00:02:51.420
crawl to the top of the monkey bars and then just jump off headfirst.
爬上单杠最高的那层然后往下跳。

53
00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:53.596
And by the time they're adults,
当他们成长为大人，

54
00:02:53.620 --> 00:02:58.396
whether they're negotiating a raise or even asking someone out on a date,
无论他们是在谈判加薪 或是约某人出去玩，

55
00:02:58.420 --> 00:03:02.316
they're habituated to take risk after risk.
他们习惯于接受一个一个挑战。

56
00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:03.580
They're rewarded for it.
他们也为此得到回报奖赏。

57
00:03:04.140 --> 00:03:06.676
It's often said in Silicon Valley,
在矽谷有这样的说法，

58
00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:10.980
no one even takes you seriously unless you've had two failed start-ups.
没人把你当回事 除非你创业失败两次以上。

59
00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:13.236
In other words,
另一句话说，

60
00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:16.356
we're raising our girls to be perfect,
我们教育培养女孩子们追求完美，

61
00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:19.700
and we're raising our boys to be brave.
我们教育培养男孩子们要勇敢。

62
00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:24.580
Some people worry about our federal deficit,
有些人担心我们的联邦赤字，

63
00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:29.420
but I, I worry about our bravery deficit.
但是，我担心我们的勇气赤字。

64
00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:33.516
Our economy, our society, we're just losing out
我们的经济，我们的社会， 我们在遭受损失，

65
00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:36.060
because we're not raising our girls to be brave.
因为我们没有教育女孩子们要勇敢。

66
00:03:36.740 --> 00:03:40.116
The bravery deficit is why women are underrepresented in STEM,
勇气赤字就是为什么女性 在科学技术工程数学（STEM）领域，

67
00:03:40.140 --> 00:03:42.076
in C-suites, in boardrooms, in Congress,
在企业高管层，在董事会，在国会，

68
00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:44.660
and pretty much everywhere you look.
在你所看到的任何地方 都未被充分代表。

69
00:03:45.820 --> 00:03:48.996
In the 1980s, psychologist Carol Dweck
在1980年代，心理学家Carol Dweck

70
00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:51.676
looked at how bright fifth graders handled an assignment
观察研究了五年级学生 如何处理一项

71
00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:53.300
that was too difficult for them.
对他们来说太困难的作业。

72
00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:57.996
She found that bright girls were quick to give up.
她发现，聪明的女孩们很快就放弃了。

73
00:03:58.020 --> 00:04:01.740
The higher the IQ, the more likely they were to give up.
智商越高的女孩， 放弃的可能性越大。

74
00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:04.076
Bright boys, on the other hand,
男孩们，

75
00:04:04.100 --> 00:04:06.796
found the difficult material to be a challenge.
将困难的材料视为一个挑战。

76
00:04:06.820 --> 00:04:08.556
They found it energizing.
他们为此精力充沛。

77
00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:11.780
They were more likely to redouble their efforts.
他们更倾向于双倍努力。

78
00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:13.740
What's going on?
发生了什么？

79
00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:15.836
Well, at the fifth grade level,
嗯，在五年级，

80
00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:19.516
girls routinely outperform boys in every subject,
女孩总的来说比男孩 在各个科目的表现都要好，

81
00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:21.676
including math and science,
包括数学和科学，

82
00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:24.540
so it's not a question of ability.
所以这不是能力的问题。

83
00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:29.500
The difference is in how boys and girls approach a challenge.
不同点在于男孩和女孩 如何看待挑战。

84
00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:32.099
And it doesn't just end in fifth grade.
这不止于五年级。

85
00:04:32.620 --> 00:04:35.796
An HP report found that men will apply for a job
一份惠普报告指出 男性会递出工作申请

86
00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:39.460
if they meet only 60 percent of the qualifications,
如果他们只达到60%的招聘要求，

87
00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:42.556
but women, women will apply
而女性，女性只有在

88
00:04:42.580 --> 00:04:47.156
only if they meet 100 percent of the qualifications.
100%达到招聘要求的时候 才会递出申请。

89
00:04:47.180 --> 00:04:48.460
100 percent.
百分之百。

90
00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:52.876
This study is usually invoked as evidence that, well,
这份研究通常会被作为 证据来说，嗯，

91
00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:54.620
women need a little more confidence.
女性需要更多的自信。

92
00:04:55.180 --> 00:04:56.676
But I think it's evidence
但我认为这是证据

93
00:04:56.700 --> 00:04:59.836
that women have been socialized to aspire to perfection,
说明女性长期被赋予 追逐完美，

94
00:04:59.860 --> 00:05:01.396
and they're overly cautious.
她们太过谨慎了。

95
00:05:01.420 --> 00:05:04.236
(Applause)
（鼓掌）

96
00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:06.316
And even when we're ambitious,
即使是当我们雄心勃勃，

97
00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:09.116
even when we're leaning in,
即使我们向前一步，

98
00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:11.356
that socialization of perfection
社会对完美的要求

99
00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:14.460
has caused us to take less risks in our careers.
让我们在职业发展中 选择冒更小的风险。

100
00:05:15.140 --> 00:05:19.716
And so those 600,000 jobs that are open right now
现在，在计算机和科技领域，

101
00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:20.980
in computing and tech,
有六十万个开放申请的工作职位，

102
00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:23.516
women are being left behind,
女性被抛在了后面，

103
00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:26.196
and it means our economy is being left behind
这也意味着我们的经济 被远远抛在了后面

104
00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:30.396
on all the innovation and problems women would solve
女性可以解决的创新和难题

105
00:05:30.420 --> 00:05:33.156
if they were socialized to be brave
如果女性被教育要勇敢

106
00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:36.260
instead of socialized to be perfect.
而不是完美。

107
00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:40.716
(Applause)
（鼓掌）

108
00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:45.076
So in 2012, I started a company to teach girls to code,
在2012年，我创办了一家公司 教女孩如何编程，

109
00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:48.156
and what I found is that by teaching them to code
我发现，通过教她们如何编程

110
00:05:48.180 --> 00:05:50.340
I had socialized them to be brave.
我令她们更加勇敢。

111
00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:55.276
Coding, it's an endless process of trial and error,
编程，是一个无止尽的过程 实验和错误，

112
00:05:55.300 --> 00:05:58.476
of trying to get the right command in the right place,
试着将对的指令放在合适的地方，

113
00:05:58.500 --> 00:06:00.916
with sometimes just a semicolon
有时只是一个分号

114
00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:04.260
making the difference between success and failure.
就能决定成功还是失败。

115
00:06:04.660 --> 00:06:07.156
Code breaks and then it falls apart,
编码出错了随后七零八落，

116
00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:09.596
and it often takes many, many tries
时常需要很多很多次试验

117
00:06:09.620 --> 00:06:11.916
until that magical moment
直到那个神奇的时刻

118
00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:15.020
when what you're trying to build comes to life.
你想要搭建的程序完成了。

119
00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:18.060
It requires perseverance.
它需要持之以恒的努力。

120
00:06:18.420 --> 00:06:21.180
It requires imperfection.
需要接受不完美。

121
00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:24.356
We immediately see in our program
我们立即发现在项目里

122
00:06:24.380 --> 00:06:26.716
our girls' fear of not getting it right,
女孩们害怕出错，

123
00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:27.980
of not being perfect.
害怕不完美。

124
00:06:28.660 --> 00:06:31.836
Every Girls Who Code teacher tells me the same story.
每个女孩的指导老师 都和我说一样的故事。

125
00:06:31.860 --> 00:06:34.836
During the first week, when the girls are learning how to code,
在第一周， 当女孩们试着学习如何编程，

126
00:06:34.860 --> 00:06:37.836
a student will call her over and she'll say,
一个学生叫她过去 她说到，

127
00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:39.876
"I don't know what code to write."
“我不知道要写那个编码。”

128
00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:41.836
The teacher will look at her screen,
当老师看她的屏幕，

129
00:06:41.860 --> 00:06:43.740
and she'll see a blank text editor.
会看到一个完全空白的界面。

130
00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:47.276
If she didn't know any better, she'd think that her student
如果她不知道原因的话， 她也许会想

131
00:06:47.300 --> 00:06:50.380
spent the past 20 minutes just staring at the screen.
她的学生在过去的20分钟里 只是盯着屏幕发呆。

132
00:06:51.220 --> 00:06:54.396
But if she presses undo a few times,
但如果她点击几下撤销键，

133
00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:58.140
she'll see that her student wrote code and then deleted it.
他就会看到她的学生 写了代码随后又删掉了它们。

134
00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:01.916
She tried, she came close,
她尝试了，她接近目标了，

135
00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:04.020
but she didn't get it exactly right.
但是她没有完全答对。

136
00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:07.476
Instead of showing the progress that she made,
比起展现她经历的过程，

137
00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:09.460
she'd rather show nothing at all.
她宁可什么都不展现。

138
00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:12.820
Perfection or bust.
要么完美要么什么也没有。

139
00:07:14.260 --> 00:07:19.020
It turns out that our girls are really good at coding,
结果显示女孩们 非常善于编程，

140
00:07:19.660 --> 00:07:21.851
but it's not enough just to teach them to code.
但教给她们如何写代码 是完全不够的。

141
00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:25.731
My friend Lev Brie, who is a professor at the University of Columbia
我的朋友Lev Brie， 是哥伦比亚大学的教授

142
00:07:25.755 --> 00:07:27.516
and teaches intro to Java
他教授Java编程

143
00:07:27.540 --> 00:07:31.220
tells me about his office hours with computer science students.
他告诉我他对电脑科学学生开放的 咨询时间里发生的故事。

144
00:07:31.940 --> 00:07:34.196
When the guys are struggling with an assignment,
当男生们艰难应对一个作业的时候，

145
00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:35.796
they'll come in and they'll say,
他们会过来然后说，

146
00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:38.180
"Professor, there's something wrong with my code."
“教授，我编的程序 出了点问题。”

147
00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:40.196
The girls will come in and say,
女生们会过来然后说，

148
00:07:40.220 --> 00:07:44.260
"Professor, there's something wrong with me."
“教授，我出了点问题。”

149
00:07:45.340 --> 00:07:48.636
We have to begin to undo the socialization of perfection,
我们必须要撤销 对女性社会化的完美主义，

150
00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:51.276
but we've got to combine it with building a sisterhood
我们必须要将这和 建立女性支持系统一起

151
00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:54.140
that lets girls know that they are not alone.
让女孩们知道 她们并不孤单。

152
00:07:54.820 --> 00:07:58.860
Because trying harder is not going to fix a broken system.
因为再努力地尝试 也无法修补一个破裂的系统。

153
00:07:59.500 --> 00:08:01.756
I can't tell you how many women tell me,
太多的女性朋友告诉我，

154
00:08:01.780 --> 00:08:03.556
"I'm afraid to raise my hand,
“我害怕举手发言，

155
00:08:03.580 --> 00:08:05.716
I'm afraid to ask a question,
我害怕问问题，

156
00:08:05.740 --> 00:08:08.116
because I don't want to be the only one
因为我不想做那个

157
00:08:08.140 --> 00:08:09.580
who doesn't understand,
那个唯一不懂的人，

158
00:08:10.180 --> 00:08:12.860
the only one who is struggling.
那个唯一挣扎的人。

159
00:08:13.660 --> 00:08:16.556
When we teach girls to be brave
当我们教女孩们要勇敢

160
00:08:16.580 --> 00:08:19.876
and we have a supportive network cheering them on,
我们要有支持她们的系统 来鼓励她们，

161
00:08:19.900 --> 00:08:22.916
they will build incredible things,
她们会有伟大的成就，

162
00:08:22.940 --> 00:08:25.660
and I see this every day.
我每天都看到这些事。

163
00:08:26.340 --> 00:08:28.956
Take, for instance, two of our high school students
举个例子， 两个高中学生

164
00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:31.356
who built a game called Tampon Run --
制作了一个游戏叫做 卫生棉逃亡-- （译者注：和游戏”神庙逃亡“谐音）

165
00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:33.836
yes, Tampon Run --
对，卫生棉逃亡--

166
00:08:33.860 --> 00:08:36.276
to fight against the menstruation taboo
来反对游戏中的月经标记

167
00:08:36.300 --> 00:08:38.500
and sexism in gaming.
和对女性的歧视。

168
00:08:39.660 --> 00:08:41.236
Or the Syrian refugee
或是叙利亚难民

169
00:08:41.260 --> 00:08:44.780
who dared show her love for her new country
她展示了对新国家的爱

170
00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:49.619
by building an app to help Americans get to the polls.
制作了一款应用程序 让美国人轻松了解民调。

171
00:08:50.580 --> 00:08:54.835
Or a 16-year-old girl who built an algorithm
或是一个16岁的女孩 她建立了一套运算系统

172
00:08:54.859 --> 00:08:59.916
to help detect whether a cancer is benign or malignant
来帮助测算癌症是 良性的还是恶性的，

173
00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:03.316
in the off chance that she can save her daddy's life
抱着一丝希望能救她

174
00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:05.900
because he has cancer.
患癌症的父亲。

175
00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:11.220
These are just three examples of thousands,
这只是成千上万个例子中的三个，

176
00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:16.036
thousands of girls who have been socialized to be imperfect,
成千上万个女孩 被社会化为不完美的，

177
00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:19.013
who have learned to keep trying, who have learned perseverance.
她们学习如何不断尝试， 学着如何持之以恒。

178
00:09:19.037 --> 00:09:21.036
And whether they become coders
无论她们未来会成为程序员

179
00:09:21.060 --> 00:09:23.716
or the next Hillary Clinton or Beyoncé,
或是下一个希拉里·克林顿 或是碧昂斯，

180
00:09:23.740 --> 00:09:27.060
they will not defer their dreams.
她们不会推迟自己的梦想。

181
00:09:27.780 --> 00:09:32.260
And those dreams have never been more important for our country.
这些梦想对我们国家来说 是多么重要。

182
00:09:33.140 --> 00:09:36.276
For the American economy, for any economy to grow,
对美国的经济， 对任何成长中的经济，

183
00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:38.436
to truly innovate,
对真正的创新开发，

184
00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:41.660
we cannot leave behind half our population.
我们不能丢下半数的人口。

185
00:09:42.460 --> 00:09:46.156
We have to socialize our girls to be comfortable with imperfection,
我们需要社会化地教女孩们 适应习惯不完美，

186
00:09:46.180 --> 00:09:49.100
and we've got to do it now.
我们现在开始就要这样做。

187
00:09:50.220 --> 00:09:54.436
We cannot wait for them to learn how to be brave like I did
我们不能等到她们 自己去学习如何勇敢

188
00:09:54.460 --> 00:09:56.540
when I was 33 years old.
就像我33岁时那样。

189
00:09:57.060 --> 00:09:59.396
We have to teach them to be brave in schools
我们要教她们勇敢 在学校

190
00:09:59.420 --> 00:10:01.156
and early in their careers,
在职业起步的时期，

191
00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:04.316
when it has the most potential to impact their lives
在能够影响她们的人生 以及其他人的人生

192
00:10:04.340 --> 00:10:06.356
and the lives of others,
重要的时期，

193
00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:11.156
and we have to show them that they will be loved and accepted
要让她们知道 她们会被爱被接受

194
00:10:11.180 --> 00:10:14.236
not for being perfect
不是因为完美

195
00:10:14.260 --> 00:10:16.900
but for being courageous.
而是因为充满勇气。

196
00:10:17.660 --> 00:10:21.476
And so I need each of you to tell every young woman you know --
我需要你们每个人 告诉你认识的每个年轻女士 --

197
00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:24.916
your sister, your niece, your employee, your colleague --
你的姐妹，你的侄女， 你的雇员，你的同事 --

198
00:10:24.940 --> 00:10:27.500
to be comfortable with imperfection,
习惯接受不完美，

199
00:10:28.180 --> 00:10:30.676
because when we teach girls to be imperfect,
因为当我们告诉女孩 不必完美的时候，

200
00:10:30.700 --> 00:10:33.276
and we help them leverage it,
我们帮助她们平衡这样的关系，

201
00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:37.196
we will build a movement of young women who are brave
我们会有更多勇敢的年轻女士

202
00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:40.596
and who will build a better world for themselves
这些女士为她们自己

203
00:10:40.620 --> 00:10:44.260
and for each and every one of us.
和我们每个人建立更好的世界。

204
00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:46.196
Thank you.
谢谢。

205
00:10:46.220 --> 00:10:50.140
(Applause)
（鼓掌）

206
00:10:50.900 --> 00:10:52.100
Thank you.
谢谢。

207
00:10:57.140 --> 00:10:58.796
Chris Anderson: Reshma, thank you.
克里斯·安德森：Reshma，谢谢你。

208
00:10:58.820 --> 00:11:01.500
It's such a powerful vision you have. You have a vision.
这是非常强大的憧憬。 你很有眼光。

209
00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:05.236
Tell me how it's going.
现在进行的怎么样了。

210
00:11:05.260 --> 00:11:07.516
How many girls are involved now in your program?
现在有多少女孩 加入了你的项目活动？

211
00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:11.196
Reshma Saujani: Yeah. So in 2012, we taught 20 girls.
Reshma Saujani：是的。 在2012年，有20个女孩参与。

212
00:11:11.220 --> 00:11:14.756
This year we'll teach 40,000 in all 50 states.
今年，我们有4万名女孩 来自美国50个州。

213
00:11:14.780 --> 00:11:16.036
(Applause)
（鼓掌）

214
00:11:16.060 --> 00:11:19.116
And that number is really powerful,
这个数字真的很厉害，

215
00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:24.436
because last year we only graduated 7,500 women in computer science.
因为去年我们只有7500名女性 拿到电脑科学的学位。

216
00:11:24.460 --> 00:11:27.036
Like, the problem is so bad
问题很严重

217
00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:29.540
that we can make that type of change quickly.
所以我们才能快速做出改变。

218
00:11:30.420 --> 00:11:33.636
CA: And you're working with some of the companies in this room even,
CA：你和现在会场里一些公司合作

219
00:11:33.660 --> 00:11:35.836
who are welcoming graduates from your program?
它们欢迎你结业于 你的项目的学生吗？

220
00:11:35.860 --> 00:11:37.836
RS: Yeah, we have about 80 partners,
RS：是的，我们有 大概80个合作公司，

221
00:11:37.860 --> 00:11:39.916
from Twitter to Facebook
从推特到脸书

222
00:11:39.940 --> 00:11:44.436
to Adobe to IBM to Microsoft to Pixar to Disney,
还有Adobe，IBM，微软 皮克斯，还有迪斯尼，

223
00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:46.356
I mean, every single company out there.
我是说，每一家公司。

224
00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:48.796
And if you're not signed up, I'm going to find you,
如果你还没和我们签合作， 我会去找你，

225
00:11:48.820 --> 00:11:50.796
because we need every single tech company
因为我们需要每个科技公司

226
00:11:50.820 --> 00:11:53.596
to embed a Girls Who Code classroom in their office.
都有能够编程的女孩 在他们的办公室工作。

227
00:11:53.620 --> 00:11:56.596
CA: And you have some stories back from some of those companies
CA：你有一些故事 来自于那些公司

228
00:11:56.620 --> 00:11:58.525
that when you mix in more gender balance
当公司性别更平等的时候

229
00:11:58.549 --> 00:12:01.996
in the engineering teams, good things happen.
在工程队，有好事情发生。

230
00:12:02.020 --> 00:12:03.316
RS: Great things happen.
RS：太棒的事情了。

231
00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:06.756
I mean, I think that it's crazy to me to think about the fact
我是说，对我来说这样的事实 简直令人发疯

232
00:12:06.780 --> 00:12:10.636
that right now 85 percent of all consumer purchases are made by women.
85%的消费行为来自于女性。

233
00:12:10.660 --> 00:12:13.716
Women use social media at a rate of 600 percent more than men.
女性使用社交媒体的比率 是男性的六倍。

234
00:12:13.740 --> 00:12:15.156
We own the Internet,
我们拥有网络，

235
00:12:15.180 --> 00:12:17.636
and we should be building the companies of tomorrow.
我们未来会创建公司。

236
00:12:17.660 --> 00:12:19.836
And I think when companies have diverse teams,
我想，当公司的团队 更加多元化，

237
00:12:19.860 --> 00:12:23.276
and they have incredible women that are part of their engineering teams,
他们的工程队有卓越的女性，

238
00:12:23.300 --> 00:12:25.716
they build awesome things, and we see it every day.
他们会建造美好的建筑， 我们每天都看到这些。

239
00:12:25.740 --> 00:12:29.476
CA: Reshma, you saw the reaction there. You're doing incredibly important work.
CA：Reshma，你看到了现场观众的反应。 你在做卓越又重要的工作。

240
00:12:29.500 --> 00:12:32.796
This whole community is cheering you on. More power to you. Thank you.
整个群体都在为你欢呼打气。 希望你更加成功。谢谢。

241
00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:34.036
RS: Thank you.
RS：谢谢。

242
00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:37.900
(Applause)
（鼓掌）